Web programmer based in London, UK. Objectivist.

I have another HN account under my real name but started this one to state the case for Ayn Rand's Objectivist philosophy.

Answers to Frequently Raised Points:

1. "I loved Atlas Shrugged and the Fountainhead as a teenager, but now I'm older I see it as simplistic and flawed."

A: I'd recommend 1) reading Rand's deeper non-fiction [1], which grounds her political views in her broader philosophy and 2) re-reading her fiction, within which you might discover new complexities and nuances.

[1] The Romantic Manifesto & Introduction to Objectivist Epistemology would be a challenging intellectual workout for anyone; Philosophy: Who Needs It would be a good general overview.

2. 'How the hell did Rand think she could derive "capitalism is good" from "A is A"?'

A: This confuses a lot of people. The thing to realise is that the Rand isn't setting up a deductive system, like those of Leibniz or Spinoza, where you state a few axioms and then derive the rest of your propositions from those. Objectivism isn't geometry.

The simplest explanation is that Objectivism treats concepts, not propositions, as the basic units of knowledge. Concepts are integrations of things which exist in the world. You form the concept "society" by observing the existence of different societies. You form the concept "rights" by relating the concept "society" to the concepts "man", "ethics", and so on, then you relate those concepts to more fundamental concepts, until you reach the most basic concepts of all: existence, identity and consciousness. Chapter 6 of Introduction to Objectivist Epistemology has more on this.

3. 'How does a British guy end up a Randroid?'

I was vaguely libertarian as a teenager. I was drawn to study computer science, and later became interested in startups, as I valued transforming ideas into physical reality. Over time I became more and more convinced that the VC game tends to reward dishonesty, exploitation, and wilful self-delusion, and that capitalism was only good insofar as individual entrepreneurs were virtuous and principled.

I'd ignored Rand as I thought she had expressed the exact opposite of my opinions. Then I actually read her writings, and discovered that she agreed with all my fundamental convictions, and, furthermore, that she'd had drawn out ramifications which I'd never even considered.

4. 'Why haven't you considered $NOVEL_POINT?'

At this stage, I almost certainly have. I spent several years in my early twenties exploring many alternative philosophies, from Buddhism to Effective Altruism to Bayesianism to 1960's psychadelic counter-culture, so I consider myself knowledgable in broad intellectual trends. When you get down to essentials, most ideas in history are simply new combinations of existing premises.

Once I finally read into Objectivism in-depth, I realised that , of all the worldviews I'd encountered, it offered the most systematic set of answers to the fundamental questions. The secret to Rand's success was, in essence, applying Aristotle's philosophy to the modern world.

Anyway, I'm happy to answer honest questions from all comers - just reply to my latest comment and I'll answer when I have time.

About me:
I graduated from USC with my Master in Dec 2008 which was the worst time to graduate. I had job offers which got withdrawn. To support my self and my family I started some freelancing work for a consultant company which paid for my rent, food and bills. In addition I also started selling scrap metal and computer scrap on commission to Pakistan, Singapore and India. This was just out of nowhere when one of my friends asked me if I could find scrap for him. Luckily I knew something about the metal scrap business as it was very related to my fathers business. I spent many days and nights roaming around in LA, Texas, Bay area and N.Y to find scrap metal yards because scrap metal companies that were listed online were BIG and wanted high prices. SO for me to make some money I had to find the feeder scrap yards to these BIG companies. I was successful in bringing the company in to the market and to break even. It was and is a great learning experience. Got to know how to open a CORP, CITY permits, Business Permit, Taxes and many other legal and other logistical issues. To get it to work, I started giving references to my dad's company in Pakistan as people wanted guarantees that I was a legit person. I could have gone doing it further BUT I wanted to be part of the TECH industry as that is what I am by the love of technology. I wanted to do something I love the most. And that is TECH. So after an year I slowed down my business workings so that I can again apply for jobs in 2009 when the economy started picking up. Everyone says that was my worst decision. BUT I don't think so. Basically I did not want to look back at my life and feel that I took an easy way out and got into the family business. 
So I head out and got a job as a developer in a Security company. At first they did not give me much to work on. I took projects on my own without waiting for them. I decided to make my/and the rest of the s-engineer's life easy. So I developed a log file analyzer with UI for parsing large log files. I had no clue about C# but learn it on the way. Everyone loved the tool as it helped analyzing and finding problems in 10GB-20GB Logs easily. From the first day my aim was to work in a TECH company so I can learn the infrastructure and the in and out of how a TECH company functions. I was successful in learning all the corporate linguistic and also was and have been getting better at programming, developing and thinking of new things everyday. I still am making my way ahead. I got promoted as a team lead for the security injection team which develops bots which do different type of attacks for web application vulnerability assessments. But everyday I feel I am working for someone else and not my self. I am helping a company to achieve what it dreams about BUT not helping my dreams succeed. All the hard work seems to be done by the engineers where as the upper management taking most of the credit and pay. I am not satisfied. 
So to be happy I need to work for my self and need to find my own ground. I want to start my own company and will and prove my self that I can do it. And that's what I am working towards. I know I will get in to YC and I hope I do so in a reasonable time. Even if I dont that wont bring my moral down and I will still keep marching forward till I am standing. YC is my goal because to meet Paul Grahm would be one of the life experience which I dont want to miss.

What a surprise to find a whole thread and blog post dedicated to the search for my identity.

I consent to a benevolent search for my identity or identities. I was quite surprised to see the speed and scale of this development - another symptom of networked life.

Some of the speculation is very interesting. It's also surprising what accidental properties of my original post(s) have come under close scrutiny when people start looking for patterns.

With the awareness of being "hunted", it's surprising how quickly one becomes more cautious about many actions. Of course, I've violated the cardinal rule of my account and used this token more than once, but part of the theory we're testing is that despite using a onetime token (to hyphenate or not, that is the question), my identitiy could still be revealed.

I feel a bit like why the lucky stiff, although his persona had merit, whereas mine is accidental. Coming next week: onetimetoken t-shirts. ;)
